Join strategies, broadcast, and when not to broadcast.

Spark picks a join algorithm based on the table sizes, and any hints you give it. There are four to know.

The broadcast hash join fires when one side is at or below the auto-broadcast threshold — ten megabytes by default — or when you add a broadcast hint. It does no shuffle at all. The small side is shipped to every executor, and the join runs locally. This is the single biggest win for star-schema queries.

The sort-merge join is the default when both sides are large. It shuffles both sides. It is for big fact-to-fact joins.

The shuffle hash join fires when one side fits in memory per partition. It shuffles just that one side.

And the cartesian, or nested-loop join, is for cross joins only.

You force a broadcast by wrapping the small side in the broadcast function — or, in sequel, with the broadcast hint. But you must know when not to. Below ten megabytes, Spark broadcasts automatically. Up to about a hundred megabytes, it is safe to force. Between a hundred and five hundred, test it on your cluster. And above five hundred megabytes, do not broadcast — because a broadcast that does not fit in executor memory will run the cluster out of memory.
